WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.440
I am the Benefits, Delivery, and Decision Transformation Manager for the California

00:00:09.440 --> 00:00:10.440
Department of Transportation.

00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:13.900
Previously, I was the Data Science Manager for the City of Los Angeles as of the Center

00:00:13.900 --> 00:00:17.879
for Data Science and Public Policy at the University of Chicago.

00:00:17.879 --> 00:00:25.160
Mostly about data, tacos, Los Angeles, sunset photos, some architecture, all fun times.

00:00:25.160 --> 00:00:29.240
So here's the existential panic that wakes me up in the morning.

00:00:29.240 --> 00:00:35.279
50% of greenhouse gas emissions in California are currently caused by transportation.

00:00:35.279 --> 00:00:38.320
Your state might be slightly different or country, but it's going to be in the same

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:39.840
ballpark.

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:44.040
If you've been paying attention to the GHG world at all over the last decade and climate

00:00:44.040 --> 00:00:48.000
change and whatnot, you will know there's this big transition of that was not true in

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:49.000
2010.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:54.279
In 2010, the biggest emitter in California was power generation.

00:00:54.279 --> 00:00:57.240
That sector is very quickly decarbonizing.

00:00:57.240 --> 00:00:59.680
Who can bank wind and solar being really cheap?

00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:03.360
So you're going, great, Hunter.

00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:04.800
Buy everybody an electric car.

00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:06.120
We got this solved, right?

00:01:06.120 --> 00:01:09.800
And the answer is you are wrong.

00:01:09.800 --> 00:01:15.919
I apologize, but if you look at the lifetime total carbon emissions of transportation,

00:01:15.919 --> 00:01:18.360
electric cars are only about 50% better.

00:01:18.360 --> 00:01:26.720
And maybe if heavy industry becomes greener, maybe they'll be about 75% better than, you

00:01:26.720 --> 00:01:29.480
know, conventional gasoline driven cars.

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:30.480
Totally fine.

00:01:30.480 --> 00:01:31.480
This happens.

00:01:31.480 --> 00:01:37.879
We have a plan for this, which is we have a net zero by 2050 plan in California.

00:01:37.879 --> 00:01:42.879
The idea is California needs to have a massive reduction in something called VMT, which you

00:01:42.879 --> 00:01:47.120
hear thrown around in those jargons, stands for vehicles, miles traveled.

00:01:47.120 --> 00:01:49.480
Transportation world, much like technology world, filled with acronyms.

00:01:49.480 --> 00:01:53.680
I'm going to try to only use the tech acronyms today.

00:01:53.680 --> 00:01:55.959
So that gets us there.

00:01:56.199 --> 00:02:00.279
So California, we wrote all these plans, and we established that we have to double our

00:02:00.279 --> 00:02:05.919
transit mode share in California by 2030, and then we need to 5X it by 2050.

00:02:05.919 --> 00:02:08.039
And you're like, great.

00:02:08.039 --> 00:02:10.360
How do I take the bus?

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:18.240
So looking at this, I was actually going to ask, show of hands, who, like, regularly takes

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:19.240
public transit?

00:02:19.240 --> 00:02:23.080
And this is, like, more than a lot of talks I've given.

00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:27.399
Who takes public transit and pays cash?

00:02:27.399 --> 00:02:31.160
Who has, like, some sort of weird smart card that they have to load?

00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:32.399
Okay.

00:02:32.399 --> 00:02:33.399
Mostly smart card users.

00:02:33.399 --> 00:02:37.919
Who gets to just use normal people money, like you would go to a coffee shop?

00:02:37.919 --> 00:02:40.919
All right.

00:02:40.919 --> 00:02:43.440
Who takes an agency that is, like, super tiny?

00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:44.440
Like anybody take Dial-A-Ride?

00:02:44.440 --> 00:02:45.440
Okay.

00:02:45.440 --> 00:02:51.839
So long story short, California, you might think, is only three or four transit agencies.

00:02:51.839 --> 00:02:54.559
You got, like, LA Metro, you got BART.

00:02:54.559 --> 00:02:59.660
There are over 800 transit agencies with over 200 agencies offering fixed route service

00:02:59.660 --> 00:03:01.320
in the bus.

00:03:01.320 --> 00:03:06.720
So when you think about California, Cali TV was founded to answer this challenge, which

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:12.919
is I want to go from Santa Monica to Sacramento or wherever, and I want to be able to seamlessly

00:03:12.919 --> 00:03:16.960
plan, pay for, and execute my trip.

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:22.479
We want to unify transit in California with a common fair payment system so you're not,

00:03:22.479 --> 00:03:24.520
like, juggling all those cards.

00:03:24.520 --> 00:03:30.559
Anybody who got a smart trip card for DC just for the week can deal with that.

00:03:30.559 --> 00:03:35.639
Make sure that you have realtime data on, like, where is the bus, and then make sure

00:03:35.639 --> 00:03:40.080
it's seamless to get verification of discounts and whatnot.

00:03:40.080 --> 00:03:45.039
I'm going to try to present now that it is not as loading, and we're going to see if

00:03:45.039 --> 00:03:46.039
this works.

00:03:46.039 --> 00:03:47.039
Come on.

00:03:47.039 --> 00:03:48.039
Yes, there we go.

00:03:48.039 --> 00:03:49.039
And...

00:03:49.039 --> 00:03:50.039
All right.

00:03:50.039 --> 00:04:01.720
It does not like me at all, so we're just going to keep going this way.

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:05.399
So the things that we really do to make transit seamless, and I promise I'm going to get to

00:04:05.399 --> 00:04:11.619
our stuff soon, unify the customer experience, make sure that we are prioritizing sustainable

00:04:11.619 --> 00:04:15.539
modes of transportation, and ground it in equity first.

00:04:15.539 --> 00:04:18.980
So how do you think about a transit trip?

00:04:18.980 --> 00:04:21.420
There are three parts of the trip, right?

00:04:21.420 --> 00:04:26.260
So the first thing is, can I plan and get to the bus or the train on time?

00:04:26.260 --> 00:04:30.019
The next thing is, once I get there, can I pay for it successfully?

00:04:30.019 --> 00:04:34.660
And then third, in the United States, we have a ton of different types of transit discounts

00:04:34.660 --> 00:04:35.660
and benefits.

00:04:35.660 --> 00:04:36.660
You might be a senior.

00:04:36.660 --> 00:04:37.660
You might be a student.

00:04:37.660 --> 00:04:39.619
Your employer might pay for your trips.

00:04:39.619 --> 00:04:41.579
There's all sorts of things.

00:04:41.579 --> 00:04:43.899
If you think about California, it is big.

00:04:43.899 --> 00:04:48.339
There are tons of, like, legacy systems that you have to go interface with.

00:04:48.339 --> 00:04:52.839
So we have a philosophy of, like, transit technology needs to be like Legos.

00:04:52.839 --> 00:04:57.220
You can snap your fare payment system into your realtime passenger information system,

00:04:57.220 --> 00:05:02.899
into your benefit system, into all your different CAD AVL subsystems and whatnot.

00:05:02.899 --> 00:05:06.980
We call a lot of this work on the data front, mobility service data, which is all about

00:05:06.980 --> 00:05:07.980
providing...

00:05:07.980 --> 00:05:10.940
So now we're going to wonk out on trip planning.

00:05:11.299 --> 00:05:14.339
Providing accurate and complete information for trip planning.

00:05:14.339 --> 00:05:19.179
So you think, like, what is the vision for that?

00:05:19.179 --> 00:05:24.899
It's that you have a complete and accurate picture of what is going on at any of those

00:05:24.899 --> 00:05:27.179
800 agencies in California.

00:05:27.179 --> 00:05:30.820
And then when I pull up my phone, whether I'm in Humboldt County in the far north of

00:05:30.820 --> 00:05:37.140
California, or Imperial County down near the U.S.-Mexico border, I could find where is

00:05:37.140 --> 00:05:40.899
any bus, where is any train, what are my transfers, how much am I going to pay?

00:05:40.899 --> 00:05:44.660
And fare should easily show up on Google Maps.

00:05:44.660 --> 00:05:48.040
So the way we do this is we establish clear expectations.

00:05:48.040 --> 00:05:53.380
We assess every agency in the state using automated technologies to say, how well are

00:05:53.380 --> 00:05:54.380
you doing this?

00:05:54.380 --> 00:05:58.140
And then we provide technical assistance to go meet those goals.

00:05:58.140 --> 00:06:01.459
So what is the clear expectation?

00:06:01.459 --> 00:06:05.540
For California, for those of you who are transit nerds, you may have heard something called

00:06:05.540 --> 00:06:09.700
the General Transit Feed Specification, formerly the Google Transit Feed Specification.

00:06:09.700 --> 00:06:16.600
This is the thing that means Google Maps, Apple Maps, City Mapper, Transit, your R applications

00:06:16.600 --> 00:06:22.459
can see bus locations and bus schedules in both real-time and schedules.

00:06:22.459 --> 00:06:27.700
And then on the back-end side, we also have a set of interoperability principles for the

00:06:27.700 --> 00:06:34.019
vendors that piece together these different pieces of information to work together.

00:06:34.019 --> 00:06:37.299
Assessing progress, this is what's really fun.

00:06:37.299 --> 00:06:42.739
We take a look at all this data, and we produce in-depth assessments for each agency being

00:06:42.739 --> 00:06:49.579
like, oh, you didn't have trip information for 33% of your buses in the last year in

00:06:49.579 --> 00:06:50.820
real-time, something like that.

00:06:50.820 --> 00:06:54.619
We talk to them every year doing a collaborative list of stuff.

00:06:54.619 --> 00:06:59.660
We produce monthly public reports on public transit data quality and public transit quality,

00:06:59.660 --> 00:07:03.119
how many jobs are agencies serving, how many folks are doing.

00:07:03.119 --> 00:07:06.179
And we do this for every one of the agencies in the state that provides fixed-route bus

00:07:06.179 --> 00:07:08.019
service now.

00:07:08.019 --> 00:07:12.380
And then we do night light, and we monitor this all nightly to make sure that, like,

00:07:12.380 --> 00:07:16.859
when things break, for example, right now school year is ending.

00:07:16.859 --> 00:07:19.660
A lot of transit agencies are changing service.

00:07:19.660 --> 00:07:23.339
A lot of the smaller agencies are not telling Google that that service is changing, which

00:07:23.339 --> 00:07:27.100
means if you show up to the bus and they're using an old version of their schedule, you're

00:07:27.100 --> 00:07:28.179
going to miss your bus.

00:07:28.179 --> 00:07:31.619
So we really try to make sure that that stays on tap.

00:07:31.619 --> 00:07:36.339
And then, finally, we do a lot of technical assistance work across our whole program.

00:07:36.339 --> 00:07:41.899
We have a transit data help desk, you know, which has been really focused on getting demand-responsive

00:07:41.899 --> 00:07:43.220
transit into GTFS.

00:07:43.220 --> 00:07:46.779
That's stuff like dial-a-ride, paratransit, whatnot.

00:07:46.779 --> 00:07:51.739
We've built open-source hardware and software to produce GTFS real-time to help small agencies

00:07:51.739 --> 00:07:55.679
in rural areas to go do it who can't afford more complex systems.

00:07:55.679 --> 00:08:01.600
We've produced playbooks and documented transit stacks for different agencies, and we do interoperable

00:08:01.600 --> 00:08:03.040
development work.

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:04.040
All right.

00:08:04.040 --> 00:08:06.839
So magic universe, we've done all this work.

00:08:06.839 --> 00:08:07.839
You've now shown up.

00:08:07.839 --> 00:08:08.839
The bus is here.

00:08:08.839 --> 00:08:11.119
What's about to happen?

00:08:11.119 --> 00:08:12.959
We need a new way to pay for transit.

00:08:12.959 --> 00:08:19.160
So, you know, from what we say, paying for transit should be as easy as paying for coffee.

00:08:19.160 --> 00:08:23.160
Customers can instantly pay, tap their bank card, tap their Apple Pay, Google Pay, their

00:08:23.160 --> 00:08:25.160
mobile wallet and whatnot.

00:08:25.160 --> 00:08:27.839
In order to do this, you need three pieces of technology.

00:08:27.839 --> 00:08:31.000
One is called a fare validator, second thing is called a fare calculation software, third

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:33.000
thing is called a payment processor.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:35.599
This is tied to the...

00:08:35.599 --> 00:08:39.599
One of the things I love about Cal ITP is we hate inventing stuff, so we really try

00:08:39.599 --> 00:08:41.119
to leverage global standards.

00:08:41.119 --> 00:08:44.479
So this is how the banking system works.

00:08:44.479 --> 00:08:47.840
I did not know anything about how banks worked before I started this job, and now I know

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:52.000
perhaps a little bit too much, so...

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:57.200
But rather than try to invent our own custom flavor of how do cards, how do we take money,

00:08:57.200 --> 00:08:59.760
do we need to set up TVMs or retail networks?

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:04.599
We just said, how can we make sure that banks and, you know, standard credit and debit cards

00:09:04.599 --> 00:09:05.599
can work?

00:09:05.599 --> 00:09:11.320
So those three pieces of technology that I mentioned are over here, and they talk between

00:09:11.320 --> 00:09:16.479
the provider's bank, so this is the state of California has banking relationships, and

00:09:16.479 --> 00:09:19.919
those go talk to MasterCard Visa, it talks to your customer's bank.

00:09:19.919 --> 00:09:23.159
All of this happens basically magically.

00:09:23.159 --> 00:09:31.760
This is called the CEMV standard, and any transit agency in the country can buy this.

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:34.039
We've done standardized procurement.

00:09:34.039 --> 00:09:38.239
Anybody who's a government person knows procurement is the worst thing about government, absolutely.

00:09:38.239 --> 00:09:42.320
Maybe hiring is worse, but pretty bad.

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:49.479
So we have what we call the mobility marketplace for purchasing these types of solutions, and

00:09:49.479 --> 00:09:52.840
it's prenegotiated, it's like a bench contract, really easy.

00:09:53.520 --> 00:09:57.559
And then on a data side, what my team can do is, because that data is standardized,

00:09:57.559 --> 00:10:02.960
the types of outputs you get from CEMV banks, they've documented this, yes, you have to

00:10:02.960 --> 00:10:08.000
transmit all the data over SFTP, but it is standardized, it comes in every day.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.760
We can build merchant services for these transit agencies that helps them understand their

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:16.200
revenue per day, what type of fares they're getting, are people paying with cards or digital

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:20.799
wallets more often, and that's really focused on the transit agency's needs, joining that

00:10:20.799 --> 00:10:27.320
data with their GTFS data upstream to say, like, this route is doing more rides, whatnot,

00:10:27.320 --> 00:10:28.320
in there.

00:10:28.320 --> 00:10:31.400
Flip side of the problem in America, I'm going to talk about this very quickly, but we need

00:10:31.400 --> 00:10:33.719
to make sure that we cover the un- and underbanked.

00:10:33.719 --> 00:10:35.799
We work with different issuing partners.

00:10:35.799 --> 00:10:39.440
It's really kind of crazy, but it's much easier to get accounts.

00:10:39.440 --> 00:10:41.239
This is sort of grounded in our equity goal.

00:10:41.239 --> 00:10:44.760
I could talk for a much longer time about this, but I'm going to kind of speed through.

00:10:44.760 --> 00:10:48.919
I'm also going to speed through this, that, like, discount enrollments, you want to standardize

00:10:48.919 --> 00:10:50.119
and simplify.

00:10:50.119 --> 00:10:51.200
We have a web application.

00:10:51.200 --> 00:10:55.359
If this was a web conference, I would talk about how we do all this non-PII linking of

00:10:55.359 --> 00:10:58.119
people's identities to stuff.

00:10:58.119 --> 00:10:59.440
This is what it looks like in practice.

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:00.919
This is the Sacramento light rail.

00:11:00.919 --> 00:11:02.200
You don't need a special card.

00:11:02.200 --> 00:11:04.200
You can just go tap your credit and debit card.

00:11:04.200 --> 00:11:05.280
It works really easily.

00:11:05.280 --> 00:11:06.280
You get fair capping.

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:09.520
So this is, like, the fun data nerdery part.

00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:12.239
We have 800 transit agencies we're stewarding.

00:11:12.239 --> 00:11:16.479
That is too many to manage ETL processes for each of those agencies.

00:11:16.479 --> 00:11:21.679
So what we focus on is what we call our core data sets, which is we use these three data

00:11:21.679 --> 00:11:25.960
standards to really drive our analytics processes.

00:11:25.960 --> 00:11:29.400
So GTFS schedule, we do that every night.

00:11:29.400 --> 00:11:32.799
We do all sorts of different output analysis from that data.

00:11:32.799 --> 00:11:36.840
GTFS realtime, again, this is just, like, where is the bus and when is it going to show

00:11:36.840 --> 00:11:37.840
up at the stop?

00:11:37.840 --> 00:11:39.179
We get that data every 20 seconds.

00:11:39.179 --> 00:11:43.559
This is sort of actually gets to be big data, because you start talking about the bus location

00:11:43.559 --> 00:11:46.880
of every bus in California every 20 seconds.

00:11:46.880 --> 00:11:50.799
You can do that to do, like, level of delay analysis, speed analysis.

00:11:50.799 --> 00:11:56.880
How can you optimize where to place potential infrastructure investments?

00:11:56.880 --> 00:12:00.200
And then finally, our third standard, EMV payments, two days after the transaction is

00:12:00.200 --> 00:12:01.760
when it comes through.

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:05.039
And that powers, you know, both our payments dashboard and a lot of, like, traditional

00:12:05.039 --> 00:12:09.599
reporting type work, if you're familiar with the national transit database and stuff.

00:12:09.599 --> 00:12:10.599
So how do we do this?

00:12:10.640 --> 00:12:14.919
Again, standard, standard, standard, simplify, share your resources.

00:12:14.919 --> 00:12:20.359
So for batch processing and data warehousing and shared compute, we have a, you know, Airflow,

00:12:20.359 --> 00:12:23.320
Kubernetes and BigQuery sort of base stacked.

00:12:23.320 --> 00:12:28.599
All of our code and documentation is open source, so I encourage you to go peruse it.

00:12:28.599 --> 00:12:29.599
Let's see.

00:12:29.599 --> 00:12:32.200
Do I have the doc site open here?

00:12:32.200 --> 00:12:35.080
I do not have it open here right now.

00:12:35.080 --> 00:12:39.880
When it comes to analysis, we tend to do we have a JupyterHub.

00:12:39.880 --> 00:12:45.520
We've been pretty heavy users of Suba on top of BigQuery, which is the report for Python.

00:12:45.520 --> 00:12:47.979
Highly recommend checking it out, especially if you're there.

00:12:47.979 --> 00:12:53.520
And then finally, for reporting and presentation, haven't adopted Quarter just yet, but we do

00:12:53.520 --> 00:12:59.719
things like put together all these sort of different reports, some of which are more

00:12:59.719 --> 00:13:02.679
lightweight but even more complex.

00:13:02.679 --> 00:13:09.599
This is a whole website that is generated out of a Jupyter notebook using Suba to give

00:13:09.599 --> 00:13:16.520
you GTFS quality reports for all these agencies, so, again, web is a little slow, but you can

00:13:16.520 --> 00:13:23.640
see let's pick on Big Blue Bus, that's Santa Monica, California, and you get all this sort

00:13:23.640 --> 00:13:31.359
of information, and what's really cool about this is you do not need an analyst who has

00:13:31.359 --> 00:13:33.880
or a web user to speak it up.

00:13:33.880 --> 00:13:40.840
This is entirely generated out of a Python notebook that is linked in there.

00:13:40.840 --> 00:13:42.559
You can continue.

00:13:42.559 --> 00:13:46.119
This is just some of the elements you get in schedule.

00:13:46.119 --> 00:13:50.880
You can do these statewide analysis of what is a high-quality transit corridor.

00:13:50.880 --> 00:13:53.039
Again, this is looking at all of Los Angeles.

00:13:53.039 --> 00:13:56.479
This is something the state did not do, and the reason we were able to do this, and if

00:13:56.479 --> 00:14:00.440
you take one takeaway from this talk, it's that data standards, especially if you work

00:14:00.479 --> 00:14:04.640
in a distributed environment, are your best friend, and even if they're not perfect data,

00:14:04.640 --> 00:14:06.880
exactly the right data.

00:14:06.880 --> 00:14:11.359
When you start talking about GTFSRT kind of digging in, there's trip updates, vehicle

00:14:11.359 --> 00:14:16.159
positions, which is exactly what they say they are, again, we kind of do this over and

00:14:16.159 --> 00:14:21.440
over again, so you can see here are live or were live screenshotted bus speeds for Los

00:14:21.440 --> 00:14:24.479
Angeles, Modesto, and Oakland.

00:14:24.479 --> 00:14:29.919
Suffice to say there's a lot of traffic, but this has really been transformative in how

00:14:29.919 --> 00:14:34.559
Caltrans does its investments, because we can really now focus in on this challenge

00:14:34.559 --> 00:14:38.559
of bus speeds, which is that.

00:14:38.559 --> 00:14:43.200
Some more fun, here's a fun chart of speed variability for an individual bus route.

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:49.599
You can see that, you know, in between certain stop pair combinations, buses have averaged

